{
  "doc_id": "1754",
  "text": "The activated form of protein C (PC) cleaves activated factor V and VIII and regulates procoagulant reactions. The c-carboxyglutamic acid (Gla) domain-dependent binding of human PC to the endothelial PC receptor (EPCR) enhances activated PC (aPC) generation by~20-fold [CITATION_1] , and is critically dependent on Leu8 in the PC/ aPC x-loop [CITATION_2] . Remarkably, human FVII (hFVII) and its activated form (hFVIIa) also have Leu8 and bind to human EPCR with affinities similar to that of PC [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , but with unclear functional consequences. In mouse experiments using bolus hFVIIa infusions, EPCR has been shown to play a role in mediating tissue persistence and biodistribution of the administered hFVIIa [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . As high-dose hFVIIa is used as a hemostatic in hemophilia inhibitor patients, such observations imply a potential EPCR role in the hemostatic capacity of on-demand, or even prophylactic, hFVIIa administration in such patients.",
